title: kagurabachi
body:
[[Weekly Shounen Jump]] manga series created by [[Hokazono Takeru]] in 2023, following the story of [[Rokuhira Chihiro]].


Prior to its debut, its first chapter was leaked a week ahead of time. In response to several elements in the chapter itself, as well as the overarching discourse at the time over WSJ's line-up, the manga received an abnormal amount of attention on the online West, ironically labeling it the magazine's new torchbearer in a meme campaign comparable to that of [[Morbius (movie)|]], which then promptly led many to label it an 'industry plant'. Typical references to the meme include [[kagurabachi pose (meme)|edits and redraws]] of the "key art":[/posts/6707029] released with the manga's debut "announcement":[https://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2294136/full/]. The aftermath of the meme would see appreciation for the manga go from the ironic to the sincere, due to its genuine quality.

title: sony's_spider-man_universe
body:
Sony's Spider-Man Universe (SSU) is an American media franchise and shared universe centered on a series of superhero films produced by Columbia Pictures in association with [[marvel|Marvel Entertainment]]. Distributed by Sony Pictures Releasing, the films are based on various Marvel Comics characters and properties commonly associated with the character [[Spider-Man]], who is not prominently featured in the franchise.

Sony officially announced their new shared universe—based on various Marvel Comics properties and characters commonly associated with Spider-Man—in May 2017, with the title "Sony's Marvel Universe". By August 2018, it was being referred to as "Sony's Universe of Marvel Characters" internally at the company. In March 2019, a Sony Pictures Entertainment presentation referred to the "Sony Pictures Universe of Marvel Characters" (SPUMC), Sony announced in August 2021 that the franchise had been renamed "Sony's Spider-Man Universe" (SSU).

title: michael_keaton
body:
Michael John Douglas (born September 5, 1951), known professionally as Michael Keaton, is an American actor.
Keaton gained early recognition for his comedic roles in Night Shift (1982), Mr. Mom (1983), and [[Beetlejuice]] (1988). He gained wider stardom portraying the title superhero in [[Batman (1989)]] and [[Batman Returns]] (1992). 

Keaton experienced a career resurgence after taking a starring role as a faded actor attempting a comeback in Alejandro González Iñárritu's Birdman (2014), for which he won a Golden Globe Award for Best Actor and a nomination for the Academy Award for Best Actor. He has since acted in biographical dramas such as Spotlight (2015), The Founder (2016), The Trial of the Chicago 7 (2020), and Worth (2021). He portrayed the [[vulture (marvel)|Vulture]] in [[Spider-Man: Homecoming]] (2017)  and [[Morbius (movie)|Morbius]] (2022) while also reprising his roles as [[Batman]] in [[The Flash (movie)|]], and the title role in [[Beetlejuice Beetlejuice]] (2024).

The movie is notable for being the subject of several ironic [[meme]]s involving calling it "the most movie ever" or treating it as the "best" movie ever made, mainly due to its poor and cheesy plot, lackluster sales, as well as middling reviews despite massive marketing.

title: david_bowie
body:
[b]David Robert Jones[/b] (8 January 1947 – 10 January 2016), known professionally as [b]David Bowie[/b] (/ˈboʊi/ BOH-ee), was an [[england|English]] singer, songwriter, musician, and actor. 

A leading figure in the music industry, he is regarded as one of the most influential musicians of the 20th century. Bowie was acclaimed by critics and musicians, particularly for his innovative work during the 1970s and onwards. His career was marked by reinvention and visual presentation, and his music and stagecraft had a significant impact on popular music.

title: gremlins_(movie)
body:
A 1984 American fantasy comedy horror film directed by Joe Dante.

The story follows young man Billy Peltzer, who receives a strange creature as a pet, which then spawns other creatures that transform into aggressive imp-like monsters later known as "[[gremlin (mythology)|]]" that wreak havoc on Billy's town during [[Christmas]] Eve.

The film's depiction of gremlin has since codified the relatively new folklore creature into fantasy worldbuilding.

title: green_lantern_(movie)
body: Green Lantern is a 2011 American superhero film based on the [[DC Comics]] character of [[green lantern|the same name]]. The film stars [[Ryan Reynolds]], [[Blake Lively]], Peter Sarsgaard, Mark Strong, Angela Bassett, and Tim Robbins, with Martin Campbell directing a script by Greg Berlanti and comic book writers Michael Green and Marc Guggenheim that was subsequently rewritten by Michael Goldenberg. This was the first DC film since Catwoman (2004) not to be involved with Legendary Pictures. The film tells the story of [[Hal Jordan]], a test pilot who is selected to become the first human member of an intergalactic police force called the Green Lantern Corps; he is given a ring that grants him superpowers and must confront Parallax, a being who threatens to upset the balance of power in the universe, while a new threat rises back on Earth.

title: final_destination_(movie)
body:
[b]Final Destination[/b] is a Horror film series created by Jeffrey Reddick and developed by New Line Cinema. Each films follow a group of survivors who survive a horrific accident after one of them received a vision that shows their deaths of the incident and warn the others. Despite escaping their untimely demise, the survivors anger [[Death (entity)|]], which is portrayed as an unseen force, who despise those who cheat Death as it goes against the natural order and kills the survivors that were supposed to die horrifically. As they get killed one by one, the Survivors try to find a way to save themselves from Death's wrath.

As of 2025, there are currently six Final Destination movies including several novels and comics. Apart from "Death", the only other recurring character in the series is William Bludworth, a Funeral director who mysteriously knows, how and why Death is after the survivors while giving them advice on how to save their lives, who is played by the late Tony Todd.

title: transformers
body:
[quote][i]"MORE THAN MEETS THE EYE...!!!"[/i] - Official slogan.[/quote]

A [[science fiction]] franchise from the [[1980s_(style)|80s]] and onwards that started as a popular line of transforming [[robot]] action figures produced by "Takara (Tomy)":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tomy and [[Hasbro]].

In 1984, American toy company Hasbro licensed the Japanese [i][[Diaclone]] Car Robots[/i] toyline (1982) along with the Japanese [i][[Microman]] "Micro Change":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Micro_Change [/i]toyline (1982) from Takara and merged both series of toys to create many of the original Transformers. Takara eventually discontinued the Diaclone and Microman toylines in 1985 in favor of the Transformers rebranding in Japan.

The [[Marvel]] [[comic]]s company also contributed to the original franchise by developing the whole fictional Generation 1 universe of the series and its robot characters info and backgrounds, all created by Marvel comics writer "Bob Budiansky":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bob_Budiansky. It also published a comic book adaptation of the series during the 80s and 90s.

Due to its great success, [i]Transformers[/i] has been adapted into many animated TV shows, an animated movie, and six live-action movies.

This tag is for the series as a whole. For the original 1984 series, see [[Transformers: Generation 1]].
